ce:section.ce:para:
In this contribution, we developed a facile one-pot strategy to synthesize high-quality polymer-functionalized FCNs via an ultrasonic irradiation treatment using cigarette ash as a cheap and renewable carbon source and further explore their potential biological applications. The detailed experimental procedures are clearly described in Scheme 1
                     . Poly(ethylene oxide) (PEG) functionalized FCNs were prepared through an ultrasonic irradiation treatment of cigarette ash and PEG-SH, which was synthesized via a dehydration reaction (Fig. S1
                     ). The introduction of PEG not only improved the water dispersibility of FCNs but also endowed the FCNs with biocompatibility. Compared with a traditional preparation method, this strategy using a one-step ultrasonic treatment requires no harsh synthetic conditions or complex experimental procedures. More importantly, the resultant FCNs show excellent performance in cytotoxicity assessment and cell imaging.

The size and morphology of PEG-functionalized FCNs are clearly observed in the TEM images (Fig. 3
                     ). According to Fig. 3A, many spherical nanoparticles with a size of approximating a dozen nanometers is identified clearly by TEM. The size of these PEG-functionalized FCNs is obviously larger than that of FCNs from other preparation strategies. Moreover, an enlarged TEM image of FCNs is shown in Fig. 3B. It is observed that the diameter of the crystal region of the FCNs is approximately 2–10 nm, which is likely the cigarette ash carbon dots. Furthermore, we also observe low contrast floccule around the FCNs. These blurry areas are attributed to the PEG polymer. Based on the TEM characterization, we speculate that the hydrophilic PEG covers the FCNs and forms a spherical shape. In addition, the hydrodynamic size distribution of the FCNs was also characterized by the dynamic light scattering (DLS) technique. As shown in Fig. 4
                     , it is observed that the particle size of the FCNs is approximately 131 ± 30 nm, which corresponds to the TEM image. Moreover, the polydispersity index (PDI) of PEG-functionalized FCNs is approximately 0.320. Based on the TEM and DLS results, we confirm that PEG-functionalized FCNs are obtained through the ultrasonic irradiation treatment.
